Russell's films. I liked "The Fighter", and that was about it. I think that his cast in his films do the absolute best job that they can, and that they're really good--but I don't think he is. For whatever reason, the Academy is in love with his films. I think they're just okay, at best (besides the aforementioned "The Fighter").  But I do like that he picks different types of material. A lot of directors tend to stay in the box.......and I like that it's a story about a normal woman who did something. Those are the hardest characters to sell, I think, in terms of acting, directing, etc.

text: Hugely prolific cast that is transcended by Jennifer Lawrence, who is the real star appeal. Well and truly cements itself enough as a big "Oscar-stealing portrayal of just how demented normality is" arthouse film to be reckoned by the Academy Awards as more than a possibility. Just as seemingly over-long, condescendingly high-brow, over-acted and over-celebrated as the glittering "all smoke, no fire" Oscars themselves with such money thrown at it to make third world citizens feel more famished than they already are. As further proof that the Academy Awards celebrate film industry success stories instead of art, David O. Russell will continue to selfishly hog the short-list nominations because of stringing his puppeteer cast of chemistry, fame, brilliance and Jennifer Lawrence together to bring home more golden statues that are too good to be charitable. The above comment on all things award-winning, prestigious and seasoned honoured by the Academy Awards of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences committee whose overwhelming white male majority will recognise quality over big names and publicity is as slim as their bellies, had been an assertion for Silver Linings Playbook and American Hustle come award season. Silver Linings Playbook was a nice wee romantic drama with an edge of the characters being socially and emotionally dysfunctional but would have been nothing to Oscar voters and the general public without the strength of Mr O. Russell's name or the performances of his already popular stars Jennifer Lawrence, Bradley Cooper, Robert De Niro and Jacki Weaver who all propelled the film to become receptor to Oscars; and American Hustle had an incredible cast, hogged the award nominations, made big bucks and felt bigger and better than the film that bagged Lawrence her Oscar, although the overrated Hustle was quietly unpopular with its non-critic audience including me. Nevertheless, I think JOY looks great. It looks like everyone was at their best when shooting this film and it feels like a cinematic achievement that will and should be recognised, judging by the teaser trailer.

This is the same group of people who complained when the first teaser for Interstellar came out (remember, the one with nothing but some thoughtful voiceover and a shot of a rocket ship taking off?). text: want to really know what this trailer is about? remember the scene in it when evidently,joy is arrested  and thrown in jail? well...check out aerosmith's old video for "blind man". you'll see a woman escorted to jail. listen to the lyrics. in 1993,there was indeed a blind man, and a woman i know on a deeply personal level,who spent a month in jail for contempt of court while her own mother lay dying. she got contempt for truth. the pig who'd set her up, who brags brags brags incessantly brags he's untouchouble,descendant of gen. robert e. lee! showed everyone what he was as he hid behind his daddy in front of a courtroom of people. he's not only a financial advisor, but a tech "advisor" dictator! to. the. movies.  oh there is so much more to this little story!  where i appear to be looney,looney, looney tunes and got ahold of a keyboard, i'm actually an extroverted introvert who loathes putting my business out here for the eyes of the world. not only that,i loathe the appearance of looking like a megalomanical pathetic loser who's all about me!me! me! when the implications of what's been happening to all of us is actually about you!you!you! i'd also lost my license to teach when a client brought up the first bombing the day after in my livingroom,and i'd said it was an inside job. i wound up for the next twelve years working as a self employed maid for k.c.s high dollar clients-where i not only made a much! better living than i did teaching, but i was actually treated better with more respect than when i taught caring for people's "things" instead of children. such is education in the u.s. of a. don't ever think the world owes you a living. don't feel entitled to anything, or above anyone by class or race. bob marley said it best--- get up stand up!
author: Joy Corbin

author: Jalil Gibson

text: arrghh! in earlier post, i'd said i'd been off the air since1-92. i should have said,1-93. i'm the radio programmer who not only attempted to warn our listeners of an impending bombing,9-14-92,but advised while donating $ to request a finance report. sorry to keep referencing aerosmith, but check out lyrics for "the farm" on 9 lives. the "farm" could be reference to farming,or jail, or the looney bin,or....a certain place in virginia where c.i.a. agents are trained. i'm posting this,knowing! the risk i take doing so-after all,my baby brother was murdered by this same cabal yrs.ago because i refused to be intimidated into silence after okla. 95. as for movies,t.v.shows,music going on and back years! including intellectual property of mine! (so kind to often reference me by name)and the constant! deluge of advertising using the word (name!) joy till if i didn't already loathe the name,i sure as hell do now-and no.one.ever. not even once! asked my permission! till it finally destroyed my! family. the woman you can blame for actually! penning "barney's" song. the actual title is broken dreams.how apt. it was meant to reassure my little boy who's family was breaking up. we could'nt be allowed to even have that. i know better than to request restitution,even tho' i'm on disability and dirt poor i want my civil rights!
